value.value: A decrease in the ability of cells to respond to damaged DNA and to repair the damage. This DNA repair deficiency can be caused by mutations in the genes involved in the DNA damage response and/or DNA repair.
MicroRNA found in the peripheral blood.

label.value: Immunoglobulin Heavy Chain Complementarity Determining Region 3

value.value: An amino acid sequence within the hypervariable region of an immunoglobulin heavy chain that includes parts of the variable (V), diversity (D), and joining (J) regions.
Hydronephrosis that occurs in a fetus.

label.value: Extent of Friend and Family Support of Effort to Increase Amount of Exercise

value.value: A question about the extent to which friends and family would support an individual's efforts to increase their amount of exercise.
An impediment to the flow of urine along the urinary tract, which is present at birth.
A hereditary disorder characterized by excessive oxalate production, leading to hyperoxaluria.
A cystic and dysplastic dilation of the distal ureter within the bladder that may extend into the bladder neck and urethra.
The Corpus uteri, or body of uterus, is the part of the uterus above the isthmus, comprising about two thirds of the non-pregnant organ.

A lung adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of mildly and moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma cells across the alveolar walls with at least one focus of invasive carcinoma measuring more than 5 mm in greatest dimension.
Enlargement of the diameter of the ureter, which can be partial or complete.
A group of conditions comprising dysfunction of the storage and elimination of urine.
Acute kidney injury caused by ischemic necrosis of the renal cortex.

Antenatal hydronephrosis with the following clinical findings: 1) an anterior-posterior renal pelvis diameter (APRPD) of 4 to less than 7 mm at less than 28 weeks, 2) to less than10 mm at greater than or equal to 28 weeks, and 3) may have central calyceal dilation. (Adapted from: Hiep T. Nguyen, Carol B. Benson, Bryann Bromley, Jeffrey B. Campbell, Jeanne Chow, Beverly Coleman, Christopher Cooper, Jude Crino, Kassa Darge, C.D. Anthony Herndon, Anthony O. Odibo, Michael J.G. Somers, Deborah R. Stein; Multidisciplinary consensus on the classification of prenatal and postnatal urinary tract dilation (UTD classification system); Pediatric Urology; December 2014 Volume 10, Issue 6, Pages 982-998)

Antenatal hydronephrosis with the following clinical findings: 1) an anterior-posterior renal pelvis diameter (APRPD) of greater than or equal to 7mm at less than 28 weeks, 2) greater than or equal to10 mm at greater than or equal to 28 weeks, or 3) any one of the following findings: a)dilation of peripheral calyces, b) abnormal parenchymal thickness or appearance, c) visibly dilated ureter, d) an abnormal bladder, or e) the presence of oligohydramnios suspected to be related to the urinary tract. (Adapted from: Hiep T. Nguyen, Carol B. Benson, Bryann Bromley, Jeffrey B. Campbell, Jeanne Chow, Beverly Coleman, Christopher Cooper, Jude Crino, Kassa Darge, C.D. Anthony Herndon, Anthony O. Odibo, Michael J.G. Somers, Deborah R. Stein; Multidisciplinary consensus on the classification of prenatal and postnatal urinary tract dilation (UTD classification system); Pediatric Urology; December 2014 Volume 10, Issue 6, Pages 982-998)

label.value: Autosomal Dominant Polycystic Kidney Disease Type 2

value.value: Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease caused by a mutation in PKD2.

label.value: Autosomal Dominant Polycystic Kidney Disease Type I

value.value: Autosomal dominant polycystic kidney disease caused by a mutation in PKD1.
Complete or partial blockage of the ureter at the point where it enters the kidney that is present at birth.
Complete or partial blockage of the ureter at the point where it enters the bladder that is present at birth.

label.value: Other and Unspecified Female Genital Organ

value.value: A heterogeneous and/or septated cyst located in the kidney.

label.value: Medullary Cystic Kidney Disease Type I

value.value: An inherited form of cystic kidney disease that leads to fibrosis and impaired renal function as a result of defects in the MUC1 gene, which encodes mucin 1.

label.value: Medullary Cystic Kidney Disease Type II

value.value: An inherited form of cystic kidney disease leading to fibrosis and impaired renal function that is caused by mutations in the UMOD gene, which encodes uromodulin/Tamm-Horsfall mucoprotein.
A homogenous cyst located in the kidney.
Inflammation of the bladder due to irradiation.
Inflammation of the trigone of the urinary bladder.
Inflammation of both the urethra and the trigone of the urinary bladder.
Epispadias with urinary continence.
Epispadias with urinary incontinence.

label.value: Cryoglobulinemic Glomerulonephritis Secondary to Systemic Disease

value.value: Cryoglobulinemia glomerulonephritis associated with chronic disease, often inflammatory conditions.

A wide fold of peritoneum that connects the uterus to the lateral walls and floor of the pelvis, and contains the ovaries, fallopian tubes, ovarian ligaments, round ligament of the uterus, and ovarian and uterine arteries.
Glomerulonephritis characterized by proliferation of endothelial or mesangial cells, affecting the glomeruli in a focal and segmental pattern.
Glomerulonephritis in the context of Henoch-Schnlein purpura.
Gross hematuria that occurs at the end of, or immediately after voiding.

Postnatal Hydronephrosis with the following clinical findings: 1) APRPD is 10 to less than 15 mm, 2) central calyceal dilation may be present, but peripheral calyceal dilation is considered to increase risk, 3) renal parenchyma should have normal thickness and appearance, 4) the ureter is not seen, and 5) the bladder is normal. If there is central calyceal dilation but the APRPD is less than 10 mm, it is still considered UTD P1. (Adapted from: Hiep T. Nguyen, Carol B. Benson, Bryann Bromley, Jeffrey B. Campbell, Jeanne Chow, Beverly Coleman, Christopher Cooper, Jude Crino, Kassa Darge, C.D. Anthony Herndon, Anthony O. Odibo, Michael J.G. Somers, Deborah R. Stein; Multidisciplinary consensus on the classification of prenatal and postnatal urinary tract dilation (UTD classification system); Pediatric Urology; December 2014 Volume 10, Issue 6, Pages 982-998)

Postnatal Hydronephrosis with the following clinical findings: 1) APRPD is greater than or equal to 15 mm, 2) the calyces may be dilated centrally and peripherally, 3) or a dilated ureter is visible, 4) the parenchymal thickness and appearance is normal, and 5) the bladder is normal. Cases in which there is peripheral calyceal dilation but the APRPD is less than 15 mm are classified as UTD P2. (Adapted from: Hiep T. Nguyen, Carol B. Benson, Bryann Bromley, Jeffrey B. Campbell, Jeanne Chow, Beverly Coleman, Christopher Cooper, Jude Crino, Kassa Darge, C.D. Anthony Herndon, Anthony O. Odibo, Michael J.G. Somers, Deborah R. Stein; Multidisciplinary consensus on the classification of prenatal and postnatal urinary tract dilation (UTD classification system); Pediatric Urology; December 2014 Volume 10, Issue 6, Pages 982-998)

Postnatal Hydronephrosis with the following clinical findings: 1) calyceal dilation and the ureter are the same as those in UTD P2, 2) the renal parenchymal is thinned, has increased echogenicity and/or has decreased corticomedullary differentiation, or 3) the bladder is abnormal (wall thickening, ureterocele, posterior urethral dilation). Cases in which there are parenchymal abnormalities but the APRPD is less than 15 mm, are classified as UTD P3. (Adapted from: Hiep T. Nguyen, Carol B. Benson, Bryann Bromley, Jeffrey B. Campbell, Jeanne Chow, Beverly Coleman, Christopher Cooper, Jude Crino, Kassa Darge, C.D. Anthony Herndon, Anthony O. Odibo, Michael J.G. Somers, Deborah R. Stein; Multidisciplinary consensus on the classification of prenatal and postnatal urinary tract dilation (UTD classification system); Pediatric Urology; December 2014 Volume 10, Issue 6, Pages 982-998)
An autosomal dominant renal phosphate wasting disorder that results in rickets.
An autosomal recessive renal phosphate wasting disorder that results in rickets.
A condition characterized by a large capacity, thin-walled bladder and megaureter(s).
A megaureter in which there is no obstruction at the ureterovesical junction.
Any of the round ligaments including the round ligament of the liver and the round ligament of the uterus.
A megaureter in which there is no obstruction at the ureterovesical junction and no vesicoureteral reflux.
A megaureter in which there is obstruction to the flow of urine at the ureterovesical junction.
A megaureter that demonstrates retrograde urine flow without ureteral obstruction.
A megaureter in which there is retrograde flow of urine and a concomitant, episodic obstruction resulting from ureteral folding.
An out-pouching of the calyx into the renal parenchyma.
Necrosis of the renal papillae, for which no underlying cause has been identified.
Nephropathy due to hypoperfusion of the kidney.
Hypertensive nephropathy secondary to malignant hypertension.
